    <h2 class='section-heading'>Opioids</h2>

    <p>

        Recognizing an opioid overdose can be a challenging task, but it's crucial to act quickly if you suspect someone
        is experiencing one. It's better to err on the side of caution and take prompt action, as it could potentially
        save a life.

        <br><br>

        If you suspect someone is experiencing an opioid overdose, call 911 or seek medical attention immediately. Stay
        with the person and monitor their breathing and consciousness until help arrives. Administering naloxone, an
        overdose reversal medication, can be lifesaving, so if it's available, don't hesitate to use it.

        <br><br>

        Symptoms of an opioid overdose can include shallow breathing, dilated pupils, cold and moist skin, blue-tinged
        skin, weak pulse, loss of consciousness, stomachache, confusion, chest pain, unresponsiveness, shallow or
        irregular breathing, slow heart rate, choking or gurgling sounds, purple lips and fingernails, clammy skin, low
        body temperature, vomiting, seizures, and loss of coordination.

        <br><br>

        Mixing opioid drugs such as heroin, Oxycontin, Fentanyl, Morphine, Vicodin, and Percocet with other central
        nervous system depressants like alcohol and benzodiazepines such as Xanax, Klonopin, Valium, and Ativan can be
        especially dangerous because they all slow down breathing, blood pressure, heart rate, and body temperature. An
        opioid overdose can lead to oxygen deprivation, brain damage, and death. Be aware of the risks involved in
        mixing substances and take steps to prevent harm.

    </p>

