    <h2 class='section-heading'>Stimulants</h2>

    <p>

        Overamping is an overdose on a stimulant. It is a dangerous side effect of excessive
        stimulant use, including prescription drugs like Adderall, illegal drugs like cocaine and methamphetamine, and
        high doses of caffeine. Symptoms may include anxiety, panic attacks, palpitations, and chest pain. Overamping
        can cause long-term damage to the body and is a strong indication of stimulant addiction. If someone is
        overamping, it is essential to seek emergency attention immediately by calling 911.

        <br><br>

        Speedballing, the practice of mixing opioids with stimulants, is a dangerous combination that can increase the
        risk of overdose. Contrary to popular belief, opioids and stimulants do not balance each other out and can
        increase the risk of overdose.

        <br><br>

        If someone experiences a stimulant overdose, call 911 immediately. There is no antidote to stimulant overdose,
        and naloxone will not work for this type of overdose. While waiting for medical help to arrive, stay with the
        individual, provide support, encourage hydration, and remain calm.

        <br><br>

        To prevent overamping, it is important to stay hydrated, replenish electrolytes, get enough sleep, eat
        nutritious foods, and be honest with your healthcare provider about your stimulant use. If someone is
        overamping, seek medical help immediately, especially if they are experiencing chest pain.

    </p>

