    <h2 class='section-heading'>Alcohol</h2>

    <p>

        Alcohol poisoning, also known as acute alcohol intoxication, occurs when a person consumes a significant amount
        of alcohol within a short period. This hazardous condition can cause essential body functions to shut down since
        alcohol is a depressant that slows down brain function. Symptoms of alcohol poisoning include confusion,
        disorientation, vomiting, seizures, slow or irregular breathing, low body temperature, blue or pale skin, and
        unconsciousness or coma.

        <br><br>

        Seeking prompt medical attention is crucial to prevent respiratory failure, brain damage, or even death. Young
        adults and women who binge drink are at higher risk of developing alcohol poisoning. To prevent alcohol
        poisoning, it is essential to drink in moderation, know your limits, stay hydrated, eat before drinking, and
        avoid combining alcohol with other drugs.

        <br><br>

        In case of suspected alcohol poisoning, call 911 without delay. Do not leave an unconscious individual alone or
        attempt to induce vomiting. Instead, place them on the ground in a sitting or partially upright position,
        leaning forward if vomiting, and rolled onto one side if unconscious.

    </p>

